{{mergefrom|Lotah}}
'''Lota''' is a [[Hindi]] and [[Urdu]] word for 'pot'. Though it may refer to any pot, the term is most commonly employed for a container filled with water to facilitate the cleaning of one's anal region after [[defecation]].  [[Image:Lota_pic.jpg|frame|right|A stainless-steel lota]]

Cleaning is accomplished by holding the lota in the right hand and pouring water on the area to be cleansed, while the left hand is used to clean the area as the water comes down.  The assignment of tasks to each hand is important, as the use of lotas is derived from Islamic traditions where the right hand is usually used to start most everyday tasks (such as eating or drinking) and thus should not make contact with the area to be cleaned.

In most South Asian and Middle Eastern countries, the use of lotas is considered to provide a more thorough cleaning than simply using toilet paper.
 
Lotas are also sometimes used to supplicate in [[ablusion]].

The [[Muslim shower]] is a more modern alternative to the lota and is a common bathroom fixture throughout the [[Indian subcontinent|Indian Subcontinent]] as well as in many [[Arab states]].

In [[Urdu language|Urdu]] and Hindi, the word ''Lota'' is also colloquially used to refer to a person that switches loyalties, especially from one political party to another.

